# Summary

<div class="block">

![](/img/graphs/calculus/continuity.png)

Continuity states that a function has no "breaks" at a given point or throughout a given interval; this means a small change in 
the input yields a small change in the output. More precisely, it states that the limit of a function at a given value is the 
function evaluated at the given value.

More precisely, let $(X, d_X), (Y, d_Y)$ be metric spaces. Then a map $\;f: X \rightarrow Y$ is called **continuous** if for every $p \in X$ and $\epsilon > 0$, $\exists\delta > 0$ such that $\forall q \in X$, $$ d_X(p, q) < \delta \Rightarrow d_Y(f(p), \:f(q)) < \epsilon.$$

</div>

